description:
Add timing tests to verify constant-time behavior in security-critical code paths.

Flagged by: Expert review (Cryptography Engineers)
Issue: std.mem.eql used in Merkle key comparison may leak timing info

Paths needing timing verification:
1. AVL tree key comparison in BatchAVLVerifier.lookup()
2. Signature verification final comparison (schnorr.zig)
3. Point equality checks in DH tuple verification
4. BigInt comparison for range proofs

Approach:
- Use statistical timing analysis (measure variance, not just averages)
- Test with keys that differ in first byte vs last byte vs identical
- Verify timing distribution is indistinguishable (t-test or similar)
- Consider using Zig's std.time.Timer for microsecond precision

Example test pattern:
```zig
test "constant-time: key comparison timing" {
    const iterations = 10000;
    var early_diff_times: [iterations]u64 = undefined;
    var late_diff_times: [iterations]u64 = undefined;

    // Keys differing in first byte (early exit if not constant-time)
    // Keys differing in last byte (late exit if not constant-time)
    // Compare distributions - should be statistically similar
}
```

Note: May need ReleaseFast builds for meaningful timing measurements.
Reference: https://timing.attacks.cr.yp.to/programming.html
